03908nam a22005295i 9780300188943DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20122012ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001889437 a10.12987/97803001889432doi  a(DE-B1597)485895  a(OCoLC)820011223  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a304.21 aKellert, Stephen R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBirthright :bPeople and Nature in the Modern World /cStephen R. Kellert. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b33 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Biophilia -- t1. Attraction -- t2. Reason -- t3. Aversion -- t4. Exploitation -- t5. Affection -- t6. Dominion -- t7. Spirituality -- t8. Symbolism -- t9. Childhood -- t10. Design -- t11. Ethics And Everyday Life -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHuman health and well-being are inextricably linked to nature; our connection to the natural world is part of our biological inheritance. In this engaging book, a pioneer in the field of biophilia-the study of human beings' inherent affinity for nature-sets forth the first full account of nature's powerful influence on the quality of our lives. Stephen Kellert asserts that our capacities to think, feel, communicate, create, and find meaning in life all depend upon our relationship to nature. And yet our increasing disconnection and alienation from the natural world reflect how seriously we have undervalued its important role in our lives.Weaving scientific findings together with personal experiences and perspectives, Kellert explores specific human tendencies-including affection, aversion, intellect, control, aesthetics, exploitation, spirituality, and communication-to discover how they are influenced by our relationship with nature. He observes that a beneficial relationship with the natural world is an instinctual inclination, but must be earned. He discusses how we can restore the balance in our relationship by means of changes in childhood development, education, conservation, building design, ethics, and everyday life. Kellert's moving book provides exactly what is needed now: a fresh understanding of how much our essential humanity relies on being a part of the natural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHuman beingsxEffect of environment on. 0aHuman ecologyxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300188943423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300188943.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles